Forgive the interruption to your regularly scheduled programming of existential despair, but you seem to require information on the rather quaint administrative contrivance known as the [Council of Wales and the Marches](/Council_of_Wales_and_the_Marches). Don't confuse it with its far less interesting, mid-20th-century successor, the [Council for Wales and Monmouthshire](/Council_for_Wales_and_Monmouthshire), which, I assure you, is an entirely different brand of bureaucratic tedium.

***

# Council of Wales and the Marches

The [Council of Wales and the Marches](/Council_of_Wales_and_the_Marches), known in [Welsh](/Welsh_language) as *Cyngor Cymru a'r Gororau*, and burdened with the rather verbose official designation of the Court of the Council in the Dominion and Principality of Wales, and the Marches of the same, was, to put it mildly, a regional administrative body. It existed as an arm of the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England), primarily concerned with the rather persistent headache of governing the areas now recognized as modern-day [Wales](/Wales) and the often-contentious bordering territories, collectively known as the [Welsh Marches](/Welsh_Marches). One could argue it was an early, somewhat clumsy attempt at decentralization, or perhaps merely a convenient way for the Crown to delegate its more troublesome responsibilities.

